Newman, 1838a: 385. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dejean" authorityYear="1826" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Cychrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="158" pageNumber="159" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viduus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">Cychrus viduus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dejean, 1826 by monotypy. Etymology. From the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">iris</emphasis>
(rainbow) and the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="158" pageNumber="159">chroa</emphasis>
(surface of the body), probably alluding to the lustre present on the dorsal surface of adults of the sole species in the hands of Newman [feminine].
</paragraph>
